    "instruction": "Using metric.csv only, restrict analysis to these candidate services: ts-auth-service, ts-order-service, ts-route-service, ts-train-service, ts-travel-service. For each (cmdb_id, kpi_name) pair do the following:\n1) Using the full available series for that (cmdb_id, kpi_name) in metric.csv, compute the global P95 threshold.\n2) Then filter metric.csv rows to the incident window 2024-01-24 18:29:59 to 2024-01-24 18:59:59 UTC and for the same (cmdb_id, kpi_name) pair compute: total_points_in_window, num_points_exceeding_threshold (value >= P95), earliest_timestamp_of_exceeding_point (unix seconds), max_value_in_window, the P95 threshold value, and anomaly_ratio = num_points_exceeding_threshold / total_points_in_window.\nReturn a compact table (max 20 rows) of these per-(cmdb_id,kpi_name) records sorted by num_points_exceeding_threshold desc, then anomaly_ratio desc. Also include counts of how many (cmdb_id,kpi_name) pairs have num_points_exceeding_threshold > 0. Return results as JSON-serializable dict."
}

{
    "analysis": "Previous step computed global P95 thresholds for metric KPIs of the five candidate services and checked the incident-window points against those thresholds. Result: 35 (cmdb_id,kpi) pairs exceeded their P95 at least once in the window. The most affected services by count were ts-auth-service, ts-order-service, and ts-route-service. Each showed multiple KPIs (cpu, diskio, latency-50/90, mem, socket, workload) with 2/25 samples exceeding P95 (anomaly_ratio ~0.08). These metric anomalies narrow the candidate set to primarily ts-auth-service, ts-order-service, and ts-route-service, but anomalies are sparse (isolated spikes). According to the workflow, next we must use traces to localize which service in the call chain is actually faulty (trace analysis), because multiple service-level KPIs are anomalous. Trace features like error_rate, row_count, and duration_p95/mean can help identify the most downstream faulty service and whether errors/latency propagated. No error_logs were available, so traces and logs must be used for localization.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using trace.csv, focus on trace records where either cmdb_id is one of: ts-auth-service, ts-order-service, ts-route-service, ts-train-service, ts-travel-service OR trace_name mentions 'to_ts-auth-service', 'to_ts-order-service', 'to_ts-route-service', 'to_ts-train-service', or 'to_ts-travel-service'. For each (cmdb_id, trace_name) pair:\n1) Compute the global P95 threshold using the full available series for that pair.\n2) Filter rows to the incident window 2024-01-24 18:29:59 to 2024-01-24 18:59:59 UTC and compute: total_points_in_window, num_points_exceeding_threshold (value >= P95), earliest_timestamp_of_exceeding_point, max_value_in_window, p95_threshold, and anomaly_ratio = num_points_exceeding_threshold/total_points_in_window.\nReturn a compact table (max 20 rows) sorted by num_points_exceeding_threshold desc then anomaly_ratio desc, plus a count of how many (cmdb_id,trace_name) pairs had num_points_exceeding_threshold > 0. Return results as a JSON-serializable dict."
}

{
    "analysis": "We computed metric anomalies and found that ts-auth-service, ts-order-service, and ts-route-service show multiple KPIs with sparse spikes (2/25 samples exceeding global P95). Trace analysis using error_rate was misleading because many trace error_rate series are all-zero, producing p95_threshold = 0 and false positives. Given multiple service-level metric anomalies at the same level, the rules require using traces (non-zero metrics like durations, p95, row_count) to identify the most downstream faulty service. Logs may then confirm the resource-level reason. Next, we must inspect trace metrics that have meaningful (non-zero) global thresholds so we can find genuine trace anomalies and downstream faulty services among the candidate list.",
